\s+2Starting the system (X and XD ROMs)\s-2

The "X" and "XD" ROM can be started in five ways.  If there is a
floppy disk in drive 0 and no keys are pressed, the system
will boot from the floppy disk drive when RESET is pressed or the 
power switch is turned on.

If there is no floppy disk available, the system will examine the
keyboard for about three seconds.  During that time, the following
keys will perform these booting operations:

.in .5i
If the
.bx BREAK
 key is pressed, the system will enter ROM BASIC as in the old ROM.

If the 
.bx 3
 key is pressed, the system will attempt to boot from the Network 3 (RS232).

If the
.bx 4
 key is pressed, the system will boot from the Network 4 if the hardware is present.

.in 0i
If no key is pressed within three seconds, the ROM will check for a hard
disk drive.  If a drive is present, is ready, and has the correct boot track,
the system will boot directly from the hard disk drive.

If there is no hard disk drive, or it is not ready or does not have
the correct boot track, the system will display \fLDiskette?\fR and will wait
for a key to be pressed.  When a key is pressed, the ROM will repeat
all five checks.

When booting off a hard disk drive, there may be a floppy in drive 0,
but the door must be open.


\s+2New Keyboard support\s-2

The "X"/"XD" ROM keyboard driver utilizes the 
.bx CTRL
 key to allow the
full 128 ASCII characters to be generated by the keyboard.  Some codes
are intercepted when using BASIC, but are available in most other programs.

The following table shows the keystrokes required to get the new characters.
When possible the same keys that are used under LS-DOS/TRSDOS 6 were used.

.vs 14p
.in .5i
.bx CTRL
.bx ,
	produces [
.br
.bx CTRL
.bx .
	produces ]
.br
.bx CTRL
.bx /
	produces \\
.br
.bx CTRL
.bx \;
	produces ^
.br
.bx CTRL
.bx -
	produces _
.br
.bx CTRL
.bx 1
	\h'-.02i'produces ASCII Code 27 (Move cursor up)
.br
.bx CTRL
.bx 2
	\h'-.02i'produces ASCII Code 28 (Move cursor to upper left corner)
.br
.bx CTRL
.bx 3
	\h'-.02i'produces ASCII Code 29 (Move cursor to beginning of line)
.br
.bx CTRL
.bx 4
	\h'-.02i'produces ASCII Code 30
.br
.bx CTRL
.bx 5
	\h'-.02i'produces ASCII Code 127
.br
.bx CTRL
.bx 6
	\h'-.02i'produces ~
.br
.bx CTRL
.bx 7
	\h'-.02i'produces `
.br
.bx CTRL
.bx 8
	\h'-.02i'produces {
.br
.bx CTRL
.bx 9
	\h'-.02i'produces }
.br
.bx CTRL
.bx 0
	\h'-.02i'produces |
.br
.bx CTRL
.bx @
	\h'-.06i'produces ASCII Code 0 (not available using INKEY$ in BASIC)
.br
.bx CTRL
.bx :
	causes a screen print to be performed if a printer is available.
.br
.vs 11p

.in 0i
In addition to the new keystrokes, the keyboard driver allows you to adjust
how long the system will wait before starting to repeat a character.  Another
adjustment changes how quickly the repeated characters are generated.
Other controls change the way the keyboard behaves when certain keys
are pressed.   All of these items are changed by modifying memory locations.
This can be done from BASIC using PEEK and POKE, with DEBUG or using the
MEMORY command (LDOS only).


.in 1.5i
.ti -1.5i
Address 4200H/16896	This byte controls the delay between pressing a
key and the generation of the first repeat of
that key.  The higher the value, the longer the
delay.  (Initial value is 14H/20.)

.in 0i
