.in 1.5i
.ti -1.5i
Address 41FFH/16895	This byte controls the delay between each repeated
character.  The higher the value, the longer
the delay.  (Initial value is 02H/2.)

.ti -1.5i
Address 4019H/16409	This byte controls operation of the keyboard,
and two bits may be changed to force the keyboard
into specific states of operation.  All other
bits are reserved for use by the ROM and should
not be altered.

Bit 0 controls the 
.bx "CAPS LOCK"
 toggle.  If the bit
is on (1), all alphabetic keys will produce
uppercase characters.  (The default for this bit
is on.)  In BASIC, use POKE 16409,PEEK(16409) OR 1
to turn Bit 0 on and use
POKE 16409,PEEK(16409) AND 254 to turn Bit 0 off.

Bit 6 controls the 
.bx SHIFT 
.bx \(da
 emulation of the
.bx CTRL
 key.  If this bit is on (1), the
.bx SHIFT
.bx \(da
 key will produce the ASCII code 10.  If the bit is
off (0), no code will be produced, and any other
key that is pressed will be produce the code that
would be generated if the 
.bx CTRL
 key was being pressed.
(The default for this bit is off (0).)

Bit 4 controls the 
.bx BREAK
 key.  If this bit is off (0),
pressing the 
.bx BREAK
 key will cause control to divert
to 0028H.  The call to the keyboard driver will not
return to the caller unless a RET instruction has been
inserted at 0028H.   (Some operating systems do this.)
If the bit is on (1), pressing 
.bx BREAK
 will cause the
keyboard driver to return the ASCII code 1.
(The default for this bit is off (0).)


